{"parentUuid":"83e24ec7-1f50-42b0-8b1d-e0bbabd3756d","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Administrator","sessionId":"751e14c9-8310-40cc-9c7d-9bde09f8a164","version":"2.1.50","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"agile-swimming-thimble","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CeUFC2QgrEqbsB8HG72wUE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, the user chose:\n1. SQLite for DB\n2. C# WinForms for the app\n3. Open source library for DWG parsing\n\nNow let me design the database schema and overall system plan. Let me think about the schema based on the price list analysis.\n\nFrom the price list analysis:\n- 4 major categories: EPS, Glasswool, Urethane, ColorSteel/Accessories\n- Each category has product types (벽체, 볼트리스, 징크, 지붕, 라인메탈, 세라믹, 사이딩)\n\n\n- Each product type has thickness variants with different grades depending on the material (일반/난연/준불연 for EPS, 48K불연/64K불연/48K내화/64K내화 for Glasswool), plus color surcharges and separate pricing for accessories.\n\nFrom the estimate analysis, I need to structure the data to capture the estimate header with customer and project details, line items that include product specifications with quantity and pricing, and special handling for panel items that expand into four rows for name, color, thickness, and certification, plus construction materials like hangers and hi-sash.\n\nNow I'm designing the database schema to organize this pricing structure—I'll need separate tables for product categories, product types, and panel products with their thickness and grade combinations, along with pricing tiers that account for the different variants and surcharges. I'm continuing to map out the database schema with customer and estimate tables, then realizing I need to reconsider the overall structure more carefully to ensure it properly captures all the relationships and data flows.\n\nThe real challenge is handling the price list hierarchy—materials like EPS, Glasswool, and Urethane each have their own product types, thickness options, and grade variations that determine pricing, so I need to design the schema to accommodate these nested dimensions without creating redundancy.\n\nNow I'm thinking through how estimate line items actually work—each panel entry needs to capture the product name, color combination, thickness specification, certification level, quantity, and pricing, while accessories follow a simpler structure with just name, spec, quantity, and price. Let me map out a comprehensive database design that handles both of these patterns cleanly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1389,"cache_read_input_tokens":39082,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1389},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CYQHb8HXZjc59BZ6rXQb8","type":"assistant","uuid":"9e0a057b-d8a1-4a5f-a78f-891f72d6251d","timestamp":"2026-02-23T03:25:51.475Z"}
